SGID (Set Group ID):
â€¢ SGID allows a file or directory to run or behave with the group ownership of the file/directory, not the userâ€™s default group.
â€¢ Only users who are members of that group can execute/access it.
â€¢ For others (not in the group), it will not work.

Enable / Disable SGID:
chmod g+s filename or chmod 2750 filename   # enable SGID
chmod g-s filename   # disable SGID

SGID on Executable Files Example :
whereis id
cp /usr/bin/id id2
addgroup group1
chown saijain:group1 id2
usermod -aG group1 user1
chmod 2750 id2
sudo chmod 711 /home/saijain


Switch user and execute:
su user1
./id2
/home/saijain/id2

What happens ?
â€¢ user1 can execute id2 only because they are a member of group1.
â€¢ The program runs with group1 as the effective group.
â€¢ Users not in group1 cannot execute it.

Permission Meaning: 2750
2 â†’ SGID
7 â†’ Owner: rwx
5 â†’ Group: r-x
0 â†’ Others: ---

SGID on Directories Example:
mkdir dir
chmod 2770 dir
cd dir
touch file1
sudo usermod -aG kali user1
su user1
cd /home/saijain/dir
touch file2

Observation:

â€¢ file1
Owner: kali
Group: group1

â€¢ file2
Owner: user1
Group: group1

ðŸ‘‰ Even though different users created the files, both files belong to the same group (group1).
